definition.value: An unexpected death without warning.
Indicates that no answer was given.
Unexpected death of an infant less than one year of age, whose cause of death is not immediately obvious prior to investigation.
Unexpected death of a child over one year of age, which remains unexplained when all known and possible causes of death have been ruled out.
Death resulting from conditions or complications which are unique to pregnancy and occur during the antepartum, intrapartum, or postpartum period.

Death resulting from previously existing disease or a disease developing during pregnancy which was not associated with gestation, but which was aggravated by the unique physiologic changes of pregnancy. Examples of indirect deaths include those associated with epilepsy, diabetes, cardiac disease and hormone-dependent malignancies.

The death of a woman while pregnant or within 42 days of the end of the pregnancy, irrespective of the duration or anatomic site of the pregnancy, due to any cause related to or aggravated by the pregnancy or its management, but not from accidental or incidental causes.
A test tube, capillary tube, or other tube designed for the collection of blood.
A blood collection tube that contains a vacuum, allowing it to draw blood through a needle to fill the tube.
A person who shares a house with another person.

Hepatic necrosis, inflammation, or scarring due to any cause that persists for more than 6 months. Manifestations may include signs and symptoms of cholestasis, portal hypertension, and/or abnormal liver function tests.
An identifying designation assigned to an individual that corresponds with their function.
A title that describes the function of a designated group, governing body, or institution.
A fetus of 16-20 weeks gestational age that shows signs of life at birth but dies after delivery.

An age group comprised of infants delivered after full 37 weeks gestation whose 5 minute Apgar score was above 7, has no major congenital anomalies and was discharged home with mother without any additional diagnoses except for physiologic hyperbilirubinemia.
An age group comprised of healthy newborns whose only diagnoses are those related to prematurity.
An age group comprised of infants greater than or equal to 34 weeks, 0 days and less than 37 weeks, 0 days gestational age.
An age group comprised of infants less than 28 weeks, 0 days gestational age.
An age group comprised of infants greater than or equal to 42 weeks, 0 days gestational age.
Having no significant health-related issues.
A laboratory test to determine the concentration of a substance that will inhibit a biological or biochemical function, such as microorganism growth or enzymatic activity.
Irreversible absence of cortical and brain stem functioning.
Interventions or procedures not otherwise categorized.
Death of a live newborn during the first 7 days of life.
Death of live newborn between 7and 27 days after birth.
Symptoms, physical examination results, and/or laboratory test results related to the female reproductive system.
Fetal or infant death during the period of time that includes the antepartum, intrapartum, and neonatal stages.
An age group comprised of infants greater than 28 weeks, 0 days and less than 34 weeks, 0 days.
Death of a live newborn during the first 24 hours of life
Death between 28 days and 1 year of life.
A response indicating that a person has lost their ability for fine movement: cannot button, write, eat, etc., or minor loss of sensitivity.
A human biological structure, fluid or other substance; excludes single molecular entities.

A bacterial toxin produced by Shigella dysenteriae and by some strains of E. coli that inhibits protein synthesis by blocking the interaction of ribosomal RNA with peptide elongation factors.  The non-catalytic beta subunit of Shiga toxin may be useful as a fusion vector for induction of antigen-specific cytotoxic T lymphocyte responses.
Observed to be or have been pregnant.
A death of the embryo occurring inside the uterus.
A death of the fetus occurring inside the uterus.
A general term comprising tissue that is not hardened or calcified; including muscle, fat, blood vessels, nerves, tendons, ligaments and fascia.
Death due to complications following an organ transplant.
The absence of disease or pathology.
Any individual with whom the subject attends or attended the same school.
An anatomical structure consisting of similarly specialized cells and intercellular matrix, aggregated according to genetically determined spatial relationships, performing a specific function.
An age group comprised of infants born alive with a gestational age between 32 to less than 37 weeks.
A laboratory test to determine the lowest concentration of a substance that will inhibit a biological or biochemical function, such as microorganism growth or enzymatic activity.
The supporting connective tissue of an organ.
An individual who is receiving a transplant of a solid organ.
An individual receiving a bone marrow transplant.
A body part, organ or organ component that is formed during the embryonic stage of life of an organism.
An unborn or unhatched vertebrate in the later stages of development showing the main recognizable features of the mature being.
A female who is married to a spouse with children whom are not biologically related to her.
Pertaining to, affecting, or associated with the liver.
